        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I bring that up because
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ9GlgYqICxYzGZew_DTq-QqGMSZ-PbD1cUkTZu2aU_O523FOZfL7Pmo5JOmeu1oEv4eK9aKhZwHlikGwySoQXBNguGBKaFIPKZXQdxsXE0tJ5L9dGv0tsac7gtKQZDFoONcOBAUUHHu2cuDktqpoPwAMIpH154hYvJo8AfLlROS1Sy17kc3fHXw3WKNdYm-93lrDYkGKDCqGDAQktGe9Si5HKUaAYQIijOgUlJhtbMieC1Cx-k2Q3-c7qjWvz-fSDEpV5dLTHNbvxe74Xovmpmp1e1MsV4TJutWDI_P-uC6nU8zJiwNY5hsvSGNI-hGSqrHVwMxaA1Mt0FTDrldpX_RP0ILfzo" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Lithic
         </a>
         made an Amazonian move recently. If you haven\xe2\x80\x99t heard about the company, that\xe2\x80\x99s OK. It just became Lithic. Before that, it was
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMtuxCAMRb9mWEY8wmvBopv-BiLgyaAmEBFnqvx9mWRRybJlW_bVPTEgzLWdbqs7kk_yeG7gCvzuCyBCI8cOzefkmOJGyNGS5MbEjDQk7_7ZANaQF4ftALId05JjwFzLdUEpl-TlJi4AwE5B6acWNIoY7CgtiMSY1UBv3XCkDCWCgze0sxYgi3shbvtDfD34d4-t5XeI5xDr2juSHaecUcM441IxOrAB1Ki0MppzKZMZGadKURm6tEzRyvQY6TrzYT-mHUP8-XwizZWKU225zH398worLNeiu_G9rkfJeHooYVog3Ubx5nVZ9zMUaJ1j8gEvSlpz21EpcxvrJIS1nNk-6Mqp9qvyL_oHhEuATA" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Privacy.com
         </a>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Privacy.com issues single-use virtual cards to people who want to keep their payment information safe as they buy things across the internet.
         </strong>
         If hackers breach a site you\xe2\x80\x99ve bought something from and steal all of the credit card information, that\xe2\x80\x99s fine. The Privacy.com card you used there already self-destructed after that one use and you\xe2\x80\x99re on to the next.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When they started in 2014, single-use virtual cards weren\xe2\x80\x99t a thing. Virtual cards were barely a thing at all. To get the card product off the ground, they worked with
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ_msjRQ5W_BYjbzGgaho-QqGMAxvv1wdTFJ0yanaU_O52zFOeXL7KlU8mljvXY0Ec-yYq2YyVEwj8EbJkD1fNDEm8EzxRUJZfzJiJsNq6n5QLIf0xqcrSHF-4JS4GQxlGkqe01F7zQoL7gEKZ3QXFEtOWWPrz18wOjQ4C_mK0Ukq1lq3cur_3rBd6vzPLsALkTXubQ1gQQDFBhVDBhwwWjHOhSDkEJJAM69GhhQISi3erLcO839a6DbDF05plKte38-kWxiqlPKIc5t_V7shuu9aIHGNrcjhnqNGO20on-y1gfZnX6cMWJuKP1o6w1KStCNllBPtgaj1xqYbkJz9qldxX_TP-zwf0k" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          i2c
         </a>
         , a 20-year-old issuing company. But by 2018, CEO Bo Jiang and team realized that they needed to build their own infrastructure to support the unique needs of their own product. They rebuilt everything from the ground up as a set of
         <strong>
          issuing primitives
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Turns out, their unique needs weren\xe2\x80\x99t that unique. Scores of modern fintech companies were also looking for a
         <strong>
          more flexible and modular card issuing API
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Last year, after a year of beta testing, Privacy.com launched its own Card Issuing API, making the issuing infrastructure it built for itself available to anyone. In May this year, Privacy.com announced a
         <strong>
          $43 million Series B, led by Bessemer Venture Partners
         </strong>
         , and that it was rebranding the API-first business to
         <strong>
          Lithic
         </strong>
         and moving Privacy.com under the Lithic umbrella. Two weeks ago, the company announced a
         <strong>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUcGupCAQ_JrxhgEExAOHd9nfMC30KHmIBnDN_P32zBw2IZCuplPVVR4arkd5ufOorXtfc3ud6DLeNWFrWLqrYpljcMJIO2g1dcGpIKy2XazzsyDuEJNr5cLuvJYUPbR45M8E51J3m7N6MgHVuChltRrgicZbucAIKP3TwpcXrhAxe3T4F8vryNglt7V21sfw85B_6Nz33Z_lLe2OBXt_7AS-S1YwIVSsVKfYtuhZgUg1M5ztMSUSxGiNSIhnUFkg0Tmw51GYhxJYrPWKeWVngkbgzupVVvo8cDGoYZCi39qeuugkl4JbIYXURvBe9GiUGY0dpdQ6WCUkN4ZrmBbQwU86PBTfV9nXa6kN_O9bdFdcPtpyFGKk9u8GO6ZPg_yb6d2vHNtrxgxLwvC1tn0T-pg9r5ixUHJhhvbJZRzlROEY-7WSvB-mSYqJAGIOB03l_6T_AOC5qaY" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           $60 million Series C led by Stripes
          </a>
         </strong>
         (Not Boring Capital invested in this round).
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The Series C brings the company\xe2\x80\x99s
         <strong>
          total funding to $110 million
         </strong>
         , with the vast majority announced within the past four months, and its valuation to
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkdmK5SAQhp8muTOoicZceDEwNMxTBJeaHGmX4NLhvP2Yc5oeEJe_qqjf-oyqcKT8lGcqdby3vT5PkBGu4qFWyGMrkHdnJeFUzGzZRisXSwQToyv73wwQlPOy5gbj2bR3RlWX4qsCY8rGh1SboZquYLkF0GIDromloJklWLFFvPuqZh1EAxK-ID9ThNHLR61nGeZfA_3o67quSfuUgoZ8TCaFrt1G-6FydcbDfaWYEoRXREV_nOoZINaCSu0p7UTe1Ycz6Ev5BhapigTGKDjvu2d09WDPzO6EgjTUYf5oNewltWxgmH8fKR0eBspvNYB1LXRV266YcP6xPymjk7cNLAgllHGCJzIBX_jKxUopY1YshGLOMVObVsyajdlhweGgU2m6ezWf9__GLGOqOmUXjx7-fKgA_hXok977GVp09blDVNqDfUOob5YvLPsBEXJnbHdVXwTXlW4dI_8eeqc0bxslWxd6Z5t6Vfzf9B9DiLct" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          $800 million
         </a>
         . That\xe2\x80\x99s rapid funding, and it matches Lithic\xe2\x80\x99s rapid growth.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         While Privacy.com continues to grow, Lithic is exploding. In just over a year since
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkNuOhCAMhp9muBsDCIgXXOzNvobhUJWMguEwG99-Gd1kk6ZN-rf908_qAktMpzpiLuiTpnIeoAL85A1KgYRqhjR5p4igsudsRE4xRySXyOdpTgC79psqqQI6qtm81cXHcG1gTDlalZsNscxRycw8S9nbwQKFns2CEQZmvn11dR6CBQVvSGcMgDa1lnLkR__1oN8tzBaX7kj-re3Z2bi3lg8lRVetD8uzrPD8U59WJ_f0OdePoA_fRpFXFFOCJaGEckFwRzoQTAxCDpRy7iQjFAuBuR6N5s6O3D0Y3hfa5Wpy0fb1MUVJhVhMTO1yk1-r3mG7hPb91Opegy_nBEGbDdwNptx8L1TTAgFS4-4mXS6qw0DHhlbIG0Qj148jJWNrNGcX21b4N_0FC-2S6Q" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          announcing its Card Issuing API
         </a>
         , Lithic is handling ~20x the total payments volume (TPV) that incumbent Marqeta did in its first year with an API (2015). It\xe2\x80\x99s
         <strong>
          on pace to 2-3x TPV by the end of the year
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When a company pivots its strategy and finds enormous success out of the gate, it\xe2\x80\x99s worth studying. This piece is about Lithic, but it\xe2\x80\x99s also chock-full of lessons on
         <strong>
          primitives
         </strong>
         ,
         <strong>
          first and best customers
         </strong>
         ,
         <strong>
          APIs
         </strong>
         ,
         <strong>
          market segmentation
         </strong>
         ,
         <strong>
          growth
         </strong>
         , and
         <strong>
          how card payments work
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Operators, investors, and the fintech-curious should all be able to learn a thing or two from Lithic. We\xe2\x80\x99ll cover:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Anatomy of a Payment
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Privacy.com
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Amazon Playbook
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Lithic
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Issuer Landscape
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Size of the Prize
           </strong>
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         To understand Lithic\xe2\x80\x99s opportunity, we need to start in the nitty gritty: by understanding how payments work.
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          The Anatomy of a Payment
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Moving money around is complex.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         We make payments all day, every day. It\xe2\x80\x99s early on the east coast, so I haven\xe2\x80\x99t made one yet this morning, but judging by my credit card statement, I\xe2\x80\x99ll make between three to five payments by the time I go to sleep tonight. Most of us never think about what goes on behind the scenes; we just swipe our card or enter our card details online and trust that
         <strong>
          the balance will go down
         </strong>
         in our account and
         <strong>
          the balance will go up
         </strong>
         in the account of whoever we\xe2\x80\x99re buying from.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In between those two events, though, a bunch of stuff happens. In fact, there are at least five layers between the buyer and the merchant. I say \xe2\x80\x9cat least,\xe2\x80\x9d because many of these layers have multiple parties involved. Finix did a great job of breaking it down in
         <em>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM1uhSAQRp_msrsGEBAXLLrpaxiE0UuqYGCs9e3L1TRNCJN883OS4yzCnPJptlSQvL8Bzw1MhKMsgAiZ7AXyELxhiutWip54IzzTUpNQhikDrDYsBvMOZNvHJTiLIcVrg1IuycuMTGnmnBBsausFUJP3lrpOiw4k1ePNtbsPEB0Y-IZ8pghkMS_ErTzajwf_rO84jmYKMfxs9lwhYmlcWms-LmmuZY8eckEbfYjzE1_w_Jt71tR91RESDKecUc0441Ix2rAGlFCd0h3nUnotGKdKUWn70Urveukfgq4zb8o-XlfeTJJNTDimXEG1_fWyKyxXoxoYal33GPAcINpxAX_LwdvxpWuYIUKu7v1g8TLbdbyvepW-ZVR7bd9z1tegkn2qW_Ef-gvAg5Pd" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Understanding the Payments Stack
          </a>
         </em>
         .
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
