          <figcaption class="image-caption" style="color: #757575; font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 300; line-height: 1.4em; text-align: center;">
           Source:
           <em>
            <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM1uhSAQRp_msrsGEBAXLLrpaxiE0UuqYGCs9e3L1TRNCJN883OS4yzCnPJptlSQvL8Bzw1MhKMsgAiZ7AXyELxhiutWip54IzzTUpNQhikDrDYsBvMOZNvHJTiLIcVrg1IuycuMTGnmnBBsausFUJP3lrpOiw4k1ePNtbsPEB0Y-IZ8pghkMS_ErTzajwf_rO84jmYKMfxs9lwhYmlcWms-LmmuZY8eckEbfYjzE1_w_Jt71tR91RESDKecUc0441Ix2rAGlFCd0h3nUnotGKdKUWn70Urveukfgq4zb8o-XlfeTJJNTDimXEG1_fWyKyxXoxoYal33GPAcINpxAX_LwdvxpWuYIUKu7v1g8TLbdbyvepW-ZVR7bd9z1tegkn2qW_Ef-gvAg5Pd">
             Finix
            </a>
            (I added Lithic)
           </em>
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Broadly, there are two sides of the transaction, with rails in between:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Issuing
           </strong>
           is on the side of the person making the purchase
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Acquiring
           </strong>
           is on the side of the seller.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Card networks
           </strong>
           like Visa, MasterCard, and American Express sit in between and connect the two sides.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When a transaction occurs, each party in the stack talks to the party above and below it to decide in seconds whether to accept payment, and then move money around.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Here\xe2\x80\x99s how it works: when you swipe a card, it goes from the merchant acquirer to the card network to the issuer processor who decrypts and then approves or denies the transaction. Then the issuing bank pays the acquiring bank, who pays the merchant.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Let\xe2\x80\x99s break it down.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Card Networks.
         </strong>
         When you hear about card payments moving over Visa or MasterCard\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9crails,\xe2\x80\x9d this is what it\xe2\x80\x99s referring to. It means that they move money from payer to payee, from buyer to merchant. Card networks sit in an important spot in the payments value chain and they have the market caps to prove it. Visa and MasterCard\xe2\x80\x99s market caps are $506 and $363 billion, respectively. They also have all sorts of power; for example, the card networks set the
         <strong>
          interchange rates,
         </strong>
         which determine how much the issuing side of the stack makes on transactions.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Acquiring.
         </strong>
         When you think about the large fintech companies, chances are you\xe2\x80\x99re thinking about the
         <strong>
          merchant acquiring
         </strong>
         side of the business. Historically, when you swiped your card at a store, the
         <strong>
          payment processor
         </strong>
         gave a thumbs up or thumbs down, then facilitated money moving from the issuing side through the card network and to the
         <strong>
          acquiring bank
         </strong>
         , which then sent the money to the merchant.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Fintech giants like PayPal, Square, Adyen, and Stripe represent a recent addition to the stack called
         <strong>
          payment facilitators
         </strong>
         . They either sit on top of the payment processors, or replace the payment processors and work directly with the acquiring bank (see: Stripe + Wells Fargo) to let merchants accept online and digital payments. Stripe has a good overview of \xe2\x80\x9cpayfacs\xe2\x80\x9d
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhSAMRb_msTSAgLBgMZv5DYNQlTwFA3Um_v3wdDFJQ1ua9uYe7xCWXC575Irk84x4HWAT_NYNEKGQs0IZY7BMcd1LYUiwIjAtNYl1nAvA7uJmsZxAjnPaoncYc7o3KOWSrJbNwoAxPZfCuzkw1g-zpEy5oPtBSHh03RkiJA8WfqBcOQHZ7Ip41Ff_9eLfLSqWeEDn896a5YwBaisOd83OVxItp5xRzTjjUjHasQ6UUIPSA-dSBi0Yp0pR6czkZPBGhpeg-8K7ek4VnX9_LpNiU8Ypl5iWNn6vboftHjRzY8v7mSJeIyQ3bRAe3_jgu0mMCyQoDWsYHd7QhoGbRk7px2cD0xvDmWkfTTnktpX-Rf8ALHaFXQ" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          here
         </a>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Most of the innovation in payments over the past couple of decades has happened on the
         <strong>
          acquiring
         </strong>
         side. For the internet to live up to its promise, online merchants needed to be able to easily accept payment, and PayPal, Square, Adyen, Stripe, and others have built large businesses making that possible. In doing so, they have dramatically expanded the market. It\xe2\x80\x99s no coincidence that Stripe\xe2\x80\x99s mission is to \xe2\x80\x9cincrease the GDP of the internet.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Issuing.
         </strong>
         On the issuing side, there are two main parties:
         <strong>
          issuing banks
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          issuing processors
         </strong>
         . Issuing banks are banks that issue cards on behalf of the card networks.
         <strong>
          Issuer processors
         </strong>
         work with the card network and issuing bank to approve transactions in real-time at the point of sale. Issuer processors -- including incumbents like i2c and TSYS, newer players like Galileo and Marqeta, and
         <strong>
          Lithic
         </strong>
         -- don\xe2\x80\x99t issue cards themselves. They work with issuing banks who do.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Legacy issuer processor giants like TSYS work with big banks who are both issuing banks
         <em>
          and
         </em>
         own the customer relationship. In this case, the bank has the power. Newer players work with
         <strong>
          sponsor banks
         </strong>
         , issuing banks who provide the Bank Identification Number required but don\xe2\x80\x99t own the customer relationship. Marqeta, for example, uses Sutton Bank to issue most of its cards, whereas Lithic can work with any issuing bank its clients use.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Adding one layer to the stack, issuer processors like Lithic allow neobanks and other non-bank companies to embed financial products into their offering -- \xe2\x80\x9cembedded finance\xe2\x80\x9d -- adding another player on the issuing side: the client. Together, the client, Lithic, and a sponsor bank perform the function of a card issuer. In this model, the clients have the power and the banks are modularized.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         To date, there has been a ton of innovation on the acquiring side.
         <strong>
          Stripe, Square, PayPal, and Lightspeed are worth over half a trillion dollars combined.
         </strong>
         They made it possible to enter a traditional credit card, or connect a bank account and pay via ACH, on nearly any website to purchase items.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         There has been less innovation and value creation on the issuing side. But the issuing side is actually where more of the value is captured in the transaction. Check out this chart from
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8z7CYCAgQWLLrpNSJ-nAyaBCIgbXP7kqRSJcuW3pP95M-ZCnPKh95SqehsYz020BG-ywK1QkZ7gTwGr4mgsudMIa-ZJ5JLFMo4ZYDVhEXXvAPadrsEZ2pI8drAmHL00lZZRrm3nEy-d8IwwiiTHgYAMRELd67ZfYDoQMMX5CNFQIt-1bqVR__xoJ-t7JLmbgox_GzmWCHW0rm0NmOPHnKpJvoQ5-ef-dxyclDKKU0ABQVNMSVYEkooFwR3pAPBxCDkQCnnXjJCsRCYG2UN905x_2B4nWlXdtuuu_cZh7KOqdqU291mv19mheUy2vdjm-seQz1GiMYu4G8w9eZ7oRpniJAbdz-aelEdBqoaWiFvEI1crxQlqgkt2ae2Ff9DfwHFaJPj" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Finix
         </a>
         :
        </p>
